1.Navigation and Directory Management
- pwd: Print Working Directory - Displays the current directory path.
- ls: List - Lists files and directories in the current directory.
  -ls -l: Lists in long format, showing permissions, number of links, owner, group, size, and modification date.
  - ls -a: Includes hidden files (files starting with `.`).
- cd [directory]: Change Directory - Changes the current directory to the specified one.
  - cd : Moves up one directory.
  - cd : Moves to the home directory.
- mkdir [directory]: Make Directory - Creates a new directory.
- rmdir [directory]: Remove Directory - Deletes an empty directory.


 2. Permissions
-chmod [mode] [file]: Change Mode - Changes the permissions of a file or directory.
  - Example: `chmod 755 myfile` sets the permissions to read, write, and execute for the owner, and read and execute for others.

3.Process Management
- ps: Process Status - Lists currently running processes.
- top: Displays dynamic real-time view of the running system, including processes.
- kill [PID]: Terminates a process using its Process ID (PID).
  - kill -9 [PID]: Forcefully terminates a process.
 4.Networking and System Information
- ifconfig: Interface Configuration - Displays network configuration details.
- ping [hostname] Sends ICMP ECHO_REQUEST packets to network hosts.
- hostname: Displays or sets the systemâ€™s hostname.
- uname -a: Displays detailed information about the system.

5.Package Management (for Debian-based systems)
- apt-get update: Updates the package list.
- apt-get upgrade: Upgrades all packages.
- apt-get install [package]: Installs a new package.
- apt-get remove [package]: Removes a package.

6.File Compression and Archiving
- tar -czvf [archive.tar.gz] [directory]: Creates a compressed archive of a directory.
- tar -xzvf [archive.tar.gz]: Extracts a compressed archive.
 7. File Operations
- touch [file]: Creates an empty file or updates the timestamp of an existing file.
- cp [source] [destination]: Copy - Copies files or directories.
  - cp -r [source] [destination]: Recursively copies directories.
- mv [source] [destination]: Move - Moves or renames files or directories.
- rm [file]: Remove - Deletes files.
  - rm -r [directory]: Recursively deletes a directory and its contents.
- cat [file]: Concatenate - Displays the content of a file.
- more [file]: View file content one page at a time.
- less [file]: Similar to `more`, but allows backward movement in the file.
- head [file]: Displays the first few lines of a file.
- tail [file]: Displays the last few lines of a file.
  - tail -f [file]: Follows the output of a file in real-time (useful for logs).
